\begin_layout Standard
Imagine the algorithm starts somewhere between the far left and point (a).
 The algorithm will move to the right since the states left of the current
 state are evaluated as worse.
 When the algorithm reaches point (a) it will stop, because both surrounding
 neigbors are worse then the current state.
 In this case, the best solution is found, but what if the algorithm start
 at point (b)? It fails and won't find the best solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Different approaches to prevent this are known.
 The worst one is when the algorithm hits a local maximum, it restarts randomly
 at another state.
 Another approach is simulated annealing.
 This method is able to jump between states, at distance x.
 The distance x is lowered by every iteration.
 Eventually this method will DUNNO the local maximum.
\end_layout

